<TITLE> Survey finds disparity in MDG progress </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 24 (bdnews24.com)The Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics has found wide geographical disparity in progress toward Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). It said in most cases, remote districts of the hill tracts in the southeast, and the northeast, apart from a few other pockets in the haors and Monga-prone regions, performed worse than the most while the central and western districts did better. Launched on Sunday, the survey shows that Jhenidah, Meherpur, Munshiganj, Panchagarh and Narayanganj districts performed the best in MDG attainment while Cox's Bazar, Rangamati, Sunamganj, Khagrachharhi and Bandarban the worst. The Multiple Indicator Cluster Survey carried out in cooperation with UNICEF to determine the progress of six of the development goals related to education, health, women and children. The goals include indicators like poverty and hunger, primary education, gender equality and women's empowerment, child mortality, maternal health, HIV/AIDS and environmental sustainability. There is a wide disparity of children's enrolment in primary schools between best and worst districts raning from 90% in Jessore to 65.3% in Sunamganj. Compared to 2006, gender parity deteriorated slightly in primary education in 2009, but improved in secondary education. , comparing to the data of 2006. At the secondary level, ratio of girls to boys went up from 1.14 in 2006 to 1.17 in 2009. In the primary level it went decreased from 1.06 to 1.03. Bangladesh has done quite well in birth registration for children below five years' of age with 80% registering in 2009 compared to 63.6% in 2006. The survey also found after testing water of 13,301 tube-wells that access to clean water has come down to 85.2 percent in 2009 and arsenic exceeded the tolerable limit in 12.6 per cent houses. The Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics interviewed 7,683 people across the country until in April and May in 2009 with the assistance of United Nations Children's Fund. Shamsul Alam, who directs the survey project, presented the survey at the workshop. Planning minister AK Khandaker and planning secretary Habib Ullah Majumder and Unicef representative in Bangladesh Carel de Rooy, among others, were. 
